Reaver

1. Overview
Reaver is a tool that performs brute-force attacks against WiFi Protected Setup (WPS) PINs, aiming to recover WPA/WPA2 passphrases.  

Use cases:
- Testing WPS-enabled routers (with authorization)  
- Auditing wireless network security  
- Educational use to understand WPS vulnerabilities  

---

2. Key Features
- Automatic WPS PIN brute forcing  
- WPA/WPA2-PSK recovery  
- Works over monitor mode + packet capture tools  
- Option to delay retries (bypass lockouts)  
- Verbose output & status updates  

---

3. Installation

Debian/Ubuntu/Kali

sudo apt update
sudo apt install reaver

Arch Linux
sudo pacman -S reaver

macOS / Source build (requires wireless driver support)

---

4. Common Commands & Usage
reaver -i wlan0mon -b <BSSID> -c <channel> -a -vv
-i : interface (monitor mode)
-b : target BSSID
-c : channel
-a : auto-detect WPS
-vv: verbose mode

Optional parameters:
-K <timeout> : set time between attempts
-p <pin> : try a specific WPS PIN
-f : ignore lock-outs (use carefully)

----

5. Requirements & Warnings
Wireless adapter with monitor mode & packet injection
Router must have WPS enabled
Ethical use only (with permission
